title: robotic hand servo controlled fingers
license: Creative Commons - Attribution - Non-Commercial - Share Alike

description.text:
Servo controlled hand.
By flexing the elbow the hand will close.
The servos are controlled by a servo testing unit, so no need for arduino sketch etc.
The fingers hinges are connected with ptfe tube 4mm, and the small rods are fastened with petg 1.75.

The servo test unit box is a remix from Alex Sahka (https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:35515). And the gears to move the knob for motion control are remix from elefantman (https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:683389).
For powering the servos and testbox i used the 4 AA battery holder by devlab (https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:35515) this file is included.

The upper and lower arm piece are printed flat, and need some thermofolding. They were inspired by another arm design uploaded by laurah (https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:2066705)

3 servo MG90s
servo testing box
PTFE tube

I will upload the final BOM and building instructions.
If parts are changed i will make a notification of the uploaded/changed part.
https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=ZhDsKN0UFYg

------UPDATE-------
If you want to print this project, but you have already made my other hand https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:2171811/#files. You can use that hand for this project. Just need to print the wrist adaptor. This makes it compatible with the lower arm from this project.

1
Print all the parts.
Fingers need to printed 5 times.
Connector rod 3_5 needs to be printed 10 times
Connector rod 1_2 needs to be printed 5 times

2
Hand plate has a bending guide in the middle. Heat the plate with a heat gun. Just enough to make it flex. Bend the hand plate, so it’s become concave.
Make sure the hinge parts are perpendicular. If not push a 4mm rod through the holes. And use washers and nuts to help you make it perpendicular. Make the parts flexible with the heat gun (not to hot) and just tighten the nuts.

3
Fingers parts are connected with a 4mm PTFE tube. Drill the outer holes with a 4mm drill, and the inner holes with a 4,2 or 4.5 drill. So the inner part can move free on the PTFE tube. But has a snug fit on the outer parts
The finger connector parts (connector 1_2 and 3_5) are connected using some filament. Just push the filament through the holes, and use a lighter or welding torch to meld the filament so it locks the parts

4
The fingers are placed on the hand plate and use some screws to fasten them.

5
The upper and lower arm need to be thermoformed. First heat up the part, but be careful at the hinge parts. Better to do this multiple times so you can make little adjustments.
The hinges need to be perpendicular. So use a 4mm rod as used by the hand parts. Make sure that you do this for both hinges at the lower arm part. Then heat up the lower arm, just the middle. And rotate the arm. So the elbow and wrist part are 90 dgs rotated in opposite of each other.

6
The servo test unit needs to be taken out of its cover. Just remove the plastic. And place the servo test unit on the bottom part. And when top part is placed use screws to clap the parts together.
The servo test knob is replaced with a gear. I used the 22 teeth and the 52 teeth version. If you want to change the range of motion for the servo control, you can use other gear versions https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:683389.

7
The battery box mockup is explained here https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:35515

description.text:
This is a remix of the double doorway with bulkhead found here: https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:2609112

The changes has been made in order to make it fit Zone Mortalis terrain pieces from a well known UK manufacturer as well as fit thematically with Horus Heresy / 30K.

The extended slots on the sides has been removed, the bottom has been made a bit thinner and the aquila has been removed from the door.

To print properly the bulkhead should be scaled to about 92,5mm wide (height and thickness left alone). The door should then be scaled to the same percentage in the same axis. We also scaled the width and thickness of the door another 0.5mm after that to allow for paint without making the fit to tight.
If you do not wish to use this door with walls from the well known UK manufacturer you can of course leave the scale as is or scale it to any other dimensions you please.

This is a 1:1 scale of my boat I would like to build. It is in inches. so it would need to be scaled down for print, unless you would like to make it by hand. I am up loading a new print/design as I continue. So please follow for the journey I have planned for the future. 

Update 12/23/17

I have been working on the curve of the arc by making a bow tie and adjusting stag/stick by 2" apart to create this low poly arch. I plan to do the same with the other angles. The model has been reworked. Now this boat is 44" wide, originally it was 36" wide with a height of 22". The length will be determine with the angle of the arch. I know what you may be saying. This is a small boat, the plans are to make this boat for one person or to make a book shelf. I hope you enjoy the progress on this adventure.

12/22/17
About the print/project. I have obtain 2"x48"x.25" boards I though what could I do with this. Of course a boat was an idea as was skis, sled and a bow. I wanted to know if I could make a boat. I made a design with one, board/stick/stag, copy and paste with 5 degrees of change until I have made a half circle. Then I wanted to make a bend in the wood. Its not merged together at this point, so I could be ungrouped and shown how I placed each board until I have receive the curve I desired. So far there a few mistakes and I will start over. This is by no means ready for build. QA will be listed as I continue on this adventure.

Measure twice and cut once

I have measured out he items and found out the boards on the back and brace are acutely 6". so I will have to fix this and using only a few measuring devices and items, I will make this thing from fantasy into reality.

description.text:
Alternative fan mount for Ender 2. This is whole new design, optimized for printing and manifold (no need to repair model). It is quick solution for better part cooling without installing additional fan.

It is best printed in ABS or PETG because residual heat from nozzle can deform PLA.

Assembly steps:

  1. Remove integrated supports from printed part.
  2. Unscrew original metal cage, then unscrew heat block and fan.
  3. Fit heat block into fan assembly and screw to carriage. Remember to remove two washers or replace screws for a bit longer ones.
  4. Screw tightly but avoid too much force to prevent fan assembly break.
  5. Screw fan into front socket using ordinary metal/wood screws (approx. 12-16mm lenght, 2.6-3.2mm diam.). Original fan mounting screws are too short. It will be easier to mount fan if you cut open cable sleeve a bit. Fan can be also glued into socket (i.e. using hot glue), but it is not recommended.
  6. You can screw fan through fan guard plate or use only two screws for fan and then mount guard plate with printed pins.

description.text:
This is a variant of the Tudor Rose Box (https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:408189) with the Decorative Top Piece (https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:447110). Instead of rose-shaped spaces for the roses to be glued on to the sides of the box, I have replaced them with cylindrical spaces that contain insets for the d20 symbols. The d20 symbols were created by mirroring the D20 Cookie Cutter (https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:1987869) and resizing appropriately for the lid (which also has an inset) and the sides.

There are three different trays. (The box can hold four so, for my example, I made two of tray 3.) Tray 1 is to hold a set of dice. This is generally reserved for very lucky dice. However, since I don't have any, I put some sparkly ones in. Tray 2 has different compartments that can hold a mini, tokens and even some sticky notes. Tray 3 is an open tray, suitable for rolling dice (like a Yahtzee box) or for holding larger items (like more dice).

In the pictured example, the box was made with Colorfabb Woodfill and the insets and trays were made with Colorfabb Brassfill. Both required some sanding after printing. The Woodfill was stained with a Minwax Red Mahogany stain.

If you use the same material, be careful with the trays. The weight of the Brassfill means that the handles may not be able to support the weight. With plain PLA and ABS, that shouldn't be a problem. Even so, I recommend caution when removing the trays from the box.

description.text:
A parametric Christmas tree / tea light generator.

User can set the number of branches per layer and
a smoothness factor along with a base diameter. The
model is intended to print as a 'spiral vase' with
0 layers on the bottom to slip the tea light into.

Adjust the number of branches and their 'spikiness'
to taste and adjust the base diameter to match your tea
lights (LED of course!). Mine measures at about 38-mm
but needed a little slop to account for spiral vase
calculations and nozzle spooge. I suggest you print
1-mm oversize and adjust with some masking tape for
a snug fit.

The mathematical bits are based on Marius Kintel's
list comprehension demos, specifically the 3rd body
generated by the superformula.scad script here:
https://github.com/openscad/list-comprehension-demos

Enjoy!
Bob M, December, 2017

title: Flood's Dual Salt and Pepper Shaker

description.text:
A unique, portable and functional design with opposed, dual, slitted twist caps allowing to hold 2 different condiments in the same shaker.  
I came up with this Dual Salt n Pepper shaker mainly so it uses minimal space in my lunch bag.

Description:
A unique, portable and functional design with opposed, dual, slitted twist caps allowing to hold 2 different condiments in the same shaker. Use:
  • Slightly untwist the cap to expose the hole, shake or gently tap with finger to pour condiment.
  • Flip the shaker over and repeat steps above to pour condiment stored on the other side.
    • Specification:
  • The bottom is 54.2mm high x 19.2mm across.
  • The caps are 12.7mm high.
  • The shaker with the caps screwed in is 62.2mm high.
  • The caps have small dents at the top to indicate the location of the hole.
    • Tips:
  • Bottom printed better for me at a 60% feedrate.
  • Shaking and rattling while printing was greatly reduced by choosing rectilinear infill.
  • Use the scaffolded version if bottom part moves while printing.
  • Use non-transparent filament for better aesthetics as the different wall thickness of the bottom part gives it an irregular opacity.
  • Print the caps different colors to distinguish the condiments.
    • Caution:
  • Scaffolding can be snapped off but I recommend using a tool instead to cleanly cut it off to avoid damaging the part.
  • Only use dry foods in this shaker whether using PLA or ABS as those plastics are otherwise not food safe. Please Google for more info.
  • I would recommend dispensing the part if having to wash more than a few times, even if only used with dry foods, to avoid possible bacteria buildup. Takes just 50 mins to reprint.
    • Tools:
    Designed with Sketchup, exported with the STL plugin, GCoded with Slic3r and printed with Repetier on a Prusa i3. I had a lot of fun making this shaker and I learned a great deal. More designs to come.

title: Security Camera Box Mount
license: Creative Commons - Attribution - Non-Commercial - Share Alike

description.text:
This is something you never knew you needed. It's designed to mount a small security camera upside-down. This can be useful if you are mounting say a ceiling mount dome camera somewhere other than a ceiling, or a ptz that you want to have more down-angle versus having it upright. Depending on the camera the box is deep enough and the slot long enough that you can slide the box all the way flush with the window to eliminate glare (at the expense of some down angle). Then all you need to do is drape some black duvetyne behind the box and you have no glare (provided you print in black like I did).

The box features a beefier base with a hole sized for a 1/4-20 heatset thread, but you could also use a nut/bolt if you needed to. The slot is elongated so you can adjust where the camera lands with respect to the box. My application was for one of those $100 Amcrest PTZs (IP3M-941B), but it'll work with anything that can fit in a 120x120mm space (although the nut/bolt method will be a bit snug with this camera).

Easy print. Use supports if you don't think your printer can span the gap. I printed it open-ended down. Took a while because you should use a pretty decent fill if you're going to do a heatset.

title: Perpendicular Offset Cylinders' Intersection Template Generator

description.text: Haven't you ever needed to cut a hole in a cylinder such that another cylinder can intersect the first perpendicularly!? Well, now you can generate templates to do just that!  BAM!

The construction of a melting furnace with limited tools is an interesting challenge; many times layout of complex curves is difficult. I wanted the burner to enter tangentially to the furnace wall; thereby, creating a flame vortex. The problem is how to layout the intersection of two perpendicular cylinders onto flat paper template? I wrote a quick Processing script that does just that. Just enter the cylinderâ€™s dimensions and the intersection point, then take the resulting screenshot, scale it to the proper dimension in Photoshop, printout, then tape to the cylinder to be cut. The variables you need to define are the diameter of cylinder 1, 2 and the distance from the axis of cylinder 1 to the axis of cylinder 2. Copy the below code into your own Processing script, adjust the user defined variables, and run it; it will display your requested template. Check out my blog to see the what a 3d printer and a metal foundry can do. http://outlyingoutlier.com/2012/07/23/building-a-micro-furnace-burner-hole-template-generator/

description.text:
I don't understand why they made belt maintenance so hard on MK3. So I made a version that allows access to the belt clamps but is just as rigid. I started with the original Prusa design.

If you are able, you should print this upgrade before you first assemble your MK3. Retro-fitting will make you cry. See https://youtu.be/PZq--mrwg2w (thanks Mat1UK)

I printed versions in both ABS and PETG and they came out great. I printed with 0.35mm layer just like stock parts. I used the out-of-the-box settings in slic3r, but added 0.3mm elephant foot compensation which helps the screw holes and channel.

2/12/18 Update Prusa released R2 versions and I updated the back cover to give belt access. Need to flip over before slicing.

description.text: Based on the idea of Greg's Wade Extruder, this Extruder has an axis distance of 36 mm for use with industrial gearwheels (Module 1, sum of teeth = 72 e.g. 12 + 60).

You need:
  • Nema 17 stepper motor
  • gearwheel with 12 teeth for the motor
  • gearwheel with 60 teeth for the hobbed rod
  • hobbed rod (diameter = 8 +0/-0.05 mm, length = 56 mm, hobbing at 22.5 mm from rear end).
  • adjusting collar (DIN 705 A, inner diameter = 8 mm)
  • washer M8 (1x),washer M4 (2x), washer M3 (3x)
  • nuts M4 (2x)
  • threaded rod M4 (2x)
  • spring (proper for threaded rod M4) (2x)
  • twin hole nut DIN 547 M4 (2x)(for tensioning the springs)
  • lens head screw M3 x ? for Stepper Motor (3x)
  • rod for idler (diameter = 8 +0/-0.05 mm, length = 19 mm)
  • ball bearing 608 (3x)
  • Hot End with 10 mm diameter

The design is based loosely on Google images of various truss arch bridges around the world. One example is the New River Gorge bridge in West Virginia, USA. Features and dimensions of real bridges were altered for the simplicity of the design and to make the bridge printable. Some best practices for printing:
  • optimize print parameters for your printer, filament, etc (only you can determine the best parameters)
  • use good filament
  • level your build plate prior to printing complex parts. it's worth the few minutes it takes. always level after removing tape, or if pulling hard to remove a part.
  • make sure the build plate is clean.
  • if using blue tape, stretch it tight when applying it to the build plate.
  • pre-feed the filament 30 to 60-s before printing (i.e., run load for 30-60s)
  • do not print several complicated parts in one build (do complex parts by themselves)
  • I find that printing faster is better (probably so the filament can't ball up in one spot)
  • when the filament spool gets low, the filament can be tightly wound on the spool and the filament may not feed properly... take special care...
  • when a new spool is used, it is easy for the filament to jump outside the spool and then it will bind up later around the spool holder ruining your build
  • make sure it is easy for the filament to enter the filament feed tube. others have designed spools, mounts, etc. for that purpose. i use a small rope that forces the filament away from the spool before entering the filament feed tube.
  • if you hear clicking when printing, that may be a result of the filament wrapped around the spool and not feeding
  • make sure that there aren't any obstructions on the spool, such as some filament used to hold it in place during shipping
  • for the replicaor2, look at the blob a filament in the left front part of the build plate and then the trail of filament to the biuild location. there should be a glob, and the line of filament should be continuous and smooth
  • one way to remove parts when using blue tape is to use a very thin spatula bought in craft-art stores (advice from youtube). get one with a wide, blunt front end (not long and thin). mine is 11 mils thick (0.011") and 20-mm wide at the front. a painting spatula/scraper in hardware stores won't work and may damage the build plate. (I use blue tape so I don't have any best practices for bare plates, heated plates or for other tapes like mylar)
  • perform regular maintenance (grease, etc).
  • when I continued to have problems printing even after performing maintenance, following troublshooting instructions, changing filaments, cleaning gears, cleaning everything, optimizing print parameters, changing temperatures, etc., I bought a new extruder assembly from Makerbot and it solved all of my problems.

The z-endstop makes it easy to adjust the bed height precisely. This way it is possible make small adjustments, and to select a height where the springs for the corner screws work best.

The z-endstop requires a M4 locknut and a 30mm M4 screw. (I only had a 20mm M4 screw, and that works too). The bracket for the switch will need an extra T-nut and M3 or M4 screw, my printer came with extras that could be used.

The y-endstop does not need new hardware.

We liked Dino Kids very much and start printing a bunch of them when realized some problems with the egg´s file. It had some reversed faces and similar stuff.

Also, we wanted to print the eggs in double color.

So we redesigned the egg in two ways. One is the same puzzle egg without errors, another is the same egg in two separate files so you can print them with different colors. The last one is the egg prepared to change the filament in the middle of the print: two-colored egg but not puzzle. We did that because we were scaling down the egg and the spots were too small to manage them.

Nos gustaron mucho los Dino Kids y empezamos a imprimir un puñado cuando nos dimos cuenta de que el archivo del huevo contenía errores, caras invertidas y cosas de esas.

Así pues lo rediseñamos de dos maneras. Una es el mismo huevo pero sin errores, otro también es el mismo pero en dos archivos separados para imprimir el huevo a dos colores. El último es el archivo preparado para cambiar el filamento a mitad de impresión: dos colores pero sin puzzle. Hicimos esto porque estabamos imprimiendo los dinosaurios a una escala más pequeña y nos quedaban los puntos del huevo demasiado pequeños.

title: Dinosaur Island Deluxe - Store All the Bits!

description.text:
Update: If you don't have access to a 3D printer, or would like to support my hobby, I have opened a shop where you can purchase this set. Visit StoreAllTheBits Online Store

Are you worried your dinos will rampage through the box eating all the patrons while it is on the shelf (of course they can have all the hooligans they want, but patrons, come on!)? Worry no more - with this set of trays and boxes for storing all the Dinosaur Island pieces with room to spare. Your dinos, patrons, cash, and everything else will keep their place in your box.

While this was designed for the Deluxe version, the regular version should fit as well.

Here are some highlights for this design:

  • All tiles are stored in a single half-height tray that has individual compartments for the "extra" or custom tiles of each type. Not using custom tiles? No problem, no need to sort them out, just pull out the regular tiles.
  • Set up should go much faster since the dinos, patrons, and cash can all just be lifted out of the box and set on the table.
  • Player trays have areas to store all the bits associated with each player, so just hand out the trays and everyone should have what they need.
  • Refer to the included packing diagram if you need help putting things back in the box.
  • Dinos, cash, and patrons all sit in the deep end of the box, everything else goes on top of the player boards.

Some of the boxes are a bit oversized, but that just leaves room for growth and helps to ensure everything stays in it's place when the game box is tipped on it's side or transported. In fact, the dino cage not only stores all your dinos, but is even big enough to hold a first player token, like say, a 150% scaling of the MakerBot Pocket T-Rex Skull shown in the pictures. None of the boxes have lids. This set generally depends on the closed box to keep everything from mixing around.

Most pieces are custom designed with the exception of the card holders (and the MakerBot Pocket T-Rex skull):

Cards - 60 count - base - ICT
Cards - 60 count - lid - ICT
These are customized versions of Interlocking Card Tray - v2 by SpoonUnit. They are sized to hold sleeved cards (66.3mm x 93.75mm x 0.54mm). If your sleeved cards are different dimensions, grab SpoonUnit's file and customize to your sizes. You'll need two sets to hold all the cards. FYI - I sized each of these to hold 60 cards, which is more than is needed. Basically just combine one large stack and one small stack into each tray.

Enjoy. I printed these on a combination of my DBot and my Original Prusa i3 MK1.

2018-01-05 - Update
A full set consists of the following:

  • 2 x Cards - 60 Count - base - ICT
  • 2 x Cards - 60 Count - lid - ICT
  • 1 x Dino Cash
  • 1 x Dino Cage
  • 1 x DNA Dice
  • 1 x Modifiers
  • 1 x Paddocks Attractions Improvements Recipes
  • 1 x Patrons
  • 4 x Player Tray

Plus the T-Rex skull if you want to use it as a first player marker.

description.text: Death Watch Mandalorian Gauntlets MKII (Male) with Integrated Hinge. They are a mirror image of the Bo Katan and a close match to the gauntlets used by most male deathwatch in Star Wars the clone wars season 5 The hinge has been designed to use a common bicycle spoke as the hinge pin. You can buy these from bike shops for $2 and cut to size. The model has been modified with supports to minimize curling on the base. these will need to be removed after printing. If you would like to watch a video on how to finish these once printed to MMCC standards go here: https://youtu.be/fusLep_OiKg If you dont have a printer and would like me to print you a new version of this gauntlet, go here: http://www.stormprops.com There is also a newer version here on thingiverse to download

I advise using supports to print the hinge section cleanly, no more than 5% overhang should be enough. They will print without supports but will be a bit messing around the hinges.  
Both sides need to be glued together.  I find the best way to do this is to sand the surface and ensure both sides are level. then in a shallow dish use acetone to melt the ends and fuse each side together. to not leave the abs in the acetone for any more than 3 seconds.

description.text:
I put this together because the gimball I bought works well for more heavy cameras but not for my action cams - they are too light.
I currently use it with my YI 4K and it works very well. It required a fair amount of fine tuning (by altering the exact position of the camera and moving the weight up or down) to make sure it is really stable and you don't get sea sick from the movement.

For convenience I put most parts in one STL, which is the handle, the middle part, and one half of the bearings holder.
You need the bearing holder twice, upper and lower half. Insert the bearings onto the handle and the middle part. Insert all into the first half and glue the second half to it.

Afterwards use a 6mm threaded rod (maybe 20 cm) and some nuts (at least 4). You also need a weight to go onto the other end of the rod. It should have roughly the same weight as the camera, but you can adjust it by moving it on the bar up or down.

The camera goes onto the base plate which is printed as a separate part.

What you need:

  • 4 bearings (inliner, skateboard)
  • 20-30cm 6mm threaded rod
  • 4-6 M6 nuts
  • weight that you can put on the rod
